'''''Hot 92''''' is a [[pirate radio]] station in [[Birmingham]], England, which in October 2005, along with another local pirate station and a black interest website, reported rumours that a black girl was raped by a group of Asian men. This allegedly caused riots in the [[Lozells]] area of [[Birmingham]], leaving at least one person dead and 35 people injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-137934431.html|title=Two Afro-Caribbean Stations and a website in Britain today|date=25 October 2005|work=PTI - The Press Trust of India Ltd|accessdate=30 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/4377112.stm|title=BBC News Magazine - Urban Pirates|date=26 October 2005|work=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)|accessdate=31 December 2009}}</ref>

In November 2005, Leon Williams, then 26, pleaded guilty to charges related to helping to run an illegal broadcasting station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-138334289.html|title=Pirate radio DJ could be jailed; COURTS: Man admits running station involved in illegal broadcasts.(News) |last=John |first= Patrice |date= 4 November 2005|work=    Birmingham Mail |accessdate=27 December 2009|location=Birmingham, England}}</ref>

In January 2008, one of the people associated with the station, Ernest Uriah Griffiths, was convicted of two charges of unauthorised broadcasting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghampost.net/birmingham-business/tm_headline=pirate-radio-broadcaster-fined-pound-300&method=full&objectid=20348391&siteid=50002-name_page.html|title= Pirate radio broadcaster fined £300|last=Geary|first=Joanna |coauthors= |date=14 January 2008|work=Birmingham Post|accessdate=27 December 2009|location=Birmingham, England}}</ref>

